LEAS.1a: I would feel gratified, proud of the fruits of my efforts in a confident manner. Pleased that I have impressed them, but more gladdened that I have met my own standards of work and contributed something worthwhile and useful. While I would appreciate this thanks given in person and perhaps even feel slighted if given indirectly, the fact that my boss stopped by personally to compliment my work fills me with trepidation that there is a 'but' coming.
LEAS.1b: I assume my boss would feel that I did excellently on the project, impressed them, even. To congratulate me personally using that word choice is either default or high praise, depending on how they are. My boss would feel pleased that I have worked so diligently on this project and has the work and end product to show for it.
LEAS.2a: Depending on whether I know the project is terrible in my own standards or not, if I agree, I would feel chastised and ask for critique, disappointed in myself and my efforts. If I did not agree with this statement, I would feel mortally offended and upset, shaken a bit at how thoroughly dismissed my efforts were.
LEAS.2b: In the face of unacceptable work, my boss would feel disappointed in me and my work, resigned to dealing with me in the future as well, and wondering how so many months of effort had gone to waste with the end product being a let-down. They would have higher standards of me and my work, and demand such.
LEAS.3a: I would feel slighted, especially if the friend in question wasn't normally prone to changing their mind like that. I would've liked to have been informed of the decision as soon as it was made, and felt slightly hurt that they didn't care to inform me.
LEAS.3b: My friend would feel somewhat bad about the decision, but ultimately due to it being a bad idea for them at the time as well as the risk involved, decide that they were playing it safe and only feel a modicum of guilt at leaving me hanging like that only to change their mind.
LEAS.4a: I would feel pleased that the financial situation did not rest solely on my back, and I would indeed like to live in a better situation than I already am, but it was their choice to retain their secret until marriage was discussed. Logically, I respect this, but mentally/psychologically, I can't help but wonder what else they're hiding. Ultimately, however, this reveal is pleasing, and even exciting--being that I am already interested in marrying them without money in the picture, their financial situation is simply a bonus.
LEAS.4b: They would feel no small amount of trepidation, a small amount of fear that I would lash out or even become blinded by the money, and worry about how this might affect me, the relationship, and honesty between partners.

I would not be angry, seeing as I would give my friend the benefit of the doubt and run with the assumption that they realized there was some imminent, not previously considered risk present, and that the venture wasn’t a wise business decision. The only thing I would potentially be a bit annoyed over would be the fact that I found this information out after calling Them. If they came to this decision, they should have let me know quickly thereafter so that I wouldn’t possibly begin moving forward in business plans while I’m thinking I still have a business partner right there with me.

LEAS.4a: I would understand why this person didn’t tell me about their extreme wealth, but I would also be a bit surprised. The reason for the surprise is because if we are discussing marriage, chances are I’ve been with this person a significant amount of time, and in a serious, stable enough relationship to even begin contemplating something as serious as marriage. Based off that, they should know me well enough at this point to know I am not the type who would be with them for their money. Particularly considering the fact that I have been dating them all this time with the understanding that their financial situation was not so good. Due to this, there shouldn’t have been any doubt surrounding my decency, so why the secret was kept for so long would actually make me concerned/confused.

LEAS.1a: I would feel proud, accomplished, hopeful, enthusiastic and excited about future. I also would  feel motivated to do better and improve myself and help even more in anyway that i can. I may, depending on how important the task was to me, get taken over by a feeling of elation, like i am floating, and cry happy tears. I would feel very good about myself in that moment and have more confidence in my abilities and potential and that practice makes perfect and try not to let little hick-ups along the way discourage me from striving toward the bigger picture.
LEAS.1b: He/she would feel like they can have trust and confidence in my abilities. They would feel like they can hand me bigger, more important tasks and have higher standard for my work, which in turn may make them be harder on me and my performance. They would feel like i have much undiscovered potential and would respect my opinion and knowledge.
LEAS.2a: I would initially feel rejected, but soon after i would feel like i can improve my work and would ask for my errors on my work and how i can fix them. I would feel like maybe I didn’t understand the directions clearly or misinterpreted them, so i would try to take a different  approach if need be. I would feel like i need to prove myself more to show my real potential and wouldn’t want them to think of me as incompetent because i feel like i am good at learning and i am curious and it is important to me that people in certain areas of my life know that.
LEAS.2b: They would feel that i am not up for the task and that I am not ready. They would feel that i am incompetent and cant count on me for important things. They would feel like i dont belong with the smarter people in the office. They would feel like they dont need to give me another chance and would just use me for ordinary daily tasks that anyone could get done, as opposed to the important tasks that fall under the bigger picture and the purpose behind the system as a whole and its design.
LEAS.3a: I would feel that my friend doesn’t trust me and/or the investment opportunity. I would feel that maybe i need to do more research and would discuss with them their concerns and then try to either provide accurate explanation and knowledge as to why they are wrong or would agree with them.
LEAS.3b: They would feel like they cant trust me or the investment. They feel like we haven’t done enough research to complete the investment and need to either acquire more information or change directions in where are are investing.
LEAS.4a: I would feel different and contradictory emotions all at once, so i would have to sit down and carefully analyze each of them to find which scenario is more probable based on my idea of his character. Depending on my strongest impression of him and the trust established between us, I woud have an initial feeling or intuition, which could also be out of fear and hence, negative, intense, and inaccurate. These feelings wouldn’t typically be in any specific order, unless his reaction and/or approach signals a red flag that would be concerning to me. When he discloses the truth about his wealth, I would feel like he has a mistrust toward romantic partners in regards to money and that he has had bad past experiences with them with respect to his wealth. I would feel like I need to discuss the reason with him for better insight in regards to his reason to see if there’s an underlying or deeper issue that needs to be addressed. I might also feel jealous with a hint of anger that he used to date the type of girls who go after a guy’s money, which drastically deviates from my morals, and would reevaluate his preferences in choosing a partner. I would maybe feel a little disappointed that he didn’t use his financial means to show/do things for me that he typically would want to do for his romantic partner and feel as though i was deprived of his full and honest love. However, I would quickly get over that feeling especially if he reassures me that his intention was not to deceive me, and if we have had rich and quality experiences together regardless of his financial adversities in the relationship. I could would feel mistrust toward him in the long run that he might just keep things from me, especially important things, and keep me in the dark. Since dishonesty is a deal-breaker for me, i would try to give him a chance to earn back my trust, while i continue to remain suspicious of his intentions for some time following the incident. I could also feel that, in a completely different way, he has pure intentions and wants a partner who can accept him for who he is with all of his imperfections, and wants to make sure that his wealth is not a primary influence on his partner’s love for him, which would encourage me to have sympathy for him develope a different kind of respect toward him.
LEAS.4b: He would feel uneasy disclosing this matter at first and maybe even be hesitant. Once he does, he would feel uncertain of my internal feelings and thoughts about it and would want me to express how i feel openly. He may also remain uncertain as to why i chose to forgive him, and whether or not his wealth had a roll to play in my decision. Depending on his idea of my character and his security in both our relationship and within himself, he will choose to believe whether his fear is valid, or that it is inaccurate and decide that it may not even be significant and/or indicative of ill intentions. If he is trusting of my love, he will start to live his life normally and include me in it without factoring in concerns about his wealth. Depending on my initial reaction and handling of my feelings toward him, though, he may grow fearful of telling me the truth about other things, and start to be less vulnerable, resulting in withdrawals emotionally and intimately.

LEAS.3a: I would feel a mixture of disappointment, since a possibly beneficial future has just been closed out to me, as well as frustration and annoyance, given that the sudden shift may have resulted in the possible loss of money or opportunity for the both of us. LEAS.3b: My friend would likely feel a measure of anxiety from having to break the bad news, as well as a measure of sadness from knowing that they were backing out on something the two had agreed to. However, this might be coupled with relief, as whatever the reason driving their decision to back out might have been causing them a significant amount of stress which would have been alleviated as a result.
LEAS.4a: I would largely feel a level of surprise which I would find somewhat humorous, given how much my expectations were repealed. LEAS.1a: I would feel very proud of myself. I wouldn't be able to stop smiling, and depending on what type of project it was, for example, doing something that I have never done before or I have struggled with in the past, I would feel relieved that I am doing a good job. Also, I would secretly be very flattered, though I would try my best to keep a calm and cool demeanor in front of my boss, though as I really quiet person who keeps to herself, those who are close to me would know I would be happy as I would express my feelings around them.
LEAS.1b: How my boss would feel might depend on the context. On one hand, if my boss simply wanted his employees to get the job done and if my coworkers weren't very hardworking in general, then telling me that my work is excellent may just be a sign that they are relieved that I got the job done. On the other hand, if my boss doesn't really compliment others and the environment is competitive, I think that they really do feel impressed and in awe that I could do such a good job that they felt compelled to tell me. They might even be surprised if this is the first project that I have ever worked on under their supervision.
LEAS.2a: While I would try to keep a straight face in front of my boss and keep the mentality that I should listen to the criticism and use that to improve my work, I would feel a combination of negative emotions that would well up in me until I find myself in a private place where I can ruminate on their comments. I would definitely feel hurt and disappointed in myself. I would start to get insecure about my skills and become worried for the future (will I be unsuccessful? will I be fired?), and if I was really as hard working as I could be, I would be confused as if to what I'm doing wrong. I would also get frustrated not only at myself, but also at my boss, maybe my coworkers if they were involved, maybe try to blame factors outside of work, or simply be angry at life. Then, I would try to numb my emotions a day after that passes to get work done, though that comment will always be like a pinch at the back of my head for a while.
LEAS.2b: I think my boss would be very disappointed and me and frustrated that I'm missing the mark. They might be angry as well because I'm not pleasing them or meeting their standards.
LEAS.3a: I don't know a lot about business or investing of the sorts so this might influence my responses. I'm not sure if that means that we'll get our money back or if one person is going to keep the money invested, but either way, knowing investing is a big deal financially, I would definitely feel anger and disappointment and would let them know too, rather than keeping my emotions to myself. I would probably feel angry towards them and if they're keeping the money, I would think they were greedy and we would definitely not be friends anymore. I would also feel disappointed and upset because I had invested in something important to me, and now I'm not getting what I should. Now, if we'd only agreed and I hadn't done anything with my money yet, I probably would only feel disappointed that I was let down and that something I was looking forward is canceled. Before I'd let all of this emotion get to me however, I would definitely ask my friend questions about why they changed their mind before I come to conclusions.
LEAS.3b: Whether they are a friend that changes their mind because of malicious intent or not, I think they would definitely feel uncomfortable when they tell me they changed their mind, unless they are so malicious that they could do so nonchalantly. If my friend truly didn't mean to hurt me, they probably feel a lot of regret and worry about my reaction to their answer.
LEAS.4a: This is a really complex question to answer, because I think this situation can be explained in different ways and my feelings would depend on certain details. First of all, I believe that if I am in love, I wouldn't care if a person came from a poor or rich family, if what they did for a living earned them six figures or not a year. I would definitely understand where he would be coming from; growing up, I didn't want people to know I usually made good grades so that people wouldn't just befriend me for homework answers. That same way of thinking would apply to his situation and I would definitely empathize with him and his feelings. However, not telling me he was from a wealthy family is still kind of a lie in my eyes - but depending on if he simply concealed that info from me or acted in front of me in such a way that he deliberately wanted to appear poor actually matters a lot. Using the metaphor of my grades in high school, I never outright told other people that I made straight A's, but I never lied by saying that I couldn't figure stuff out; in his case, he would've never told me that he was from a wealthy family, but he didn't deliberately act as if he was poor. I would think to myself different questions trying to connect the dots with his past behavior, such as: "Did he really wear these type of clothes because he loves dressing comfortably, or does he do this to appear a certain way?" "How much did he lie about his childhood?" If he was simply subtly concealing his wealth and I just happened to assume he wasn't well financially, then we would probably still be okay as a couple. However, if him concealing his wealth really influenced a large part of his actions and personality, then I think I would be quite upset the more I think about the revelation. This is because is would've been essentially lying about himself - I would be in love with a lie. And ironically, despite the fact that he was looking for "genuine love," he himself wasn't genuine at all, and depending on if certain actions were performed and to the extent he tried to put on a façade, I would definitely think he was being selfish trying to change himself for me and I would end the relationship. Hopefully, it would be the former situation and not the latter. For the former, I would simply reassure him that I don't care about money and would simply be curious about his family, like I would with any other relationship.
LEAS.4b: They might feel scared or nervous that I might reject them or get upset because they've lied/haven't told the truth about their family, and that I might get intimidated by his wealth. However, another part of me feels that if they truly love me and know me for who I am, they would also feel relieved and comfortable in telling me the truth about their background because they know I would still accept them.

LEAS.1a: I would feel elated. After putting countless hours into a project, I have so much investment in it. So when someone I greatly respect gives me positive feedback on it (and excellent is a strong positive word as well, i.e more weighty than "good") I would be almost giddy with joy.
LEAS.1b: If my boss took the time to come tell me this feedback in person, instead of through an email, I would assume that he was feeling grateful for my hard work. Perhaps he would also feel more "connected" with me in the sense that now there is more trust in this professional relationship regarding my reliability.
LEAS.2a:
If I knew that I could be working harder and more efficiently (If I agreed with my boss), then I would feel saddened that my boss picked up on my deficiencies, but I would also feel motivated to do better because I would know that I have the ability to do better. I would want to work hard to change his perception of me. 
But, if I disagreed with his assessment of my work, then I would probably feel anger and feel discouraged. My motivation might decrease.
LEAS.2b: My boss might feel anger if this was a recurring pattern. He might feel optimistic if this was the first time he was telling me.
LEAS.3a: I would feel angry at her for changing her mind after she committed to our venture. I would also feel saddened that we can't continue on this project that we were so excited for. I would feel upset at myself for having such high expectations of her. I would feel upset at myself for imagining how this venture would exactly to plan.
LEAS.3b: My friend would feel hesitant to tell me that she was disinterested. She also might feel angry at me for building this idea up in my mind so much. She also might feel saddened because she really wanted to work together, but she realized later that certain commitments would get in the  way.
LEAS.4a:
I think I would feel saddened that he didn't tell me earlier. I think the amount of sadness I would  or wouldn't feel would depend on how much I felt deceived. Did he tell a lot of little white lies? Did he ever lie about something outright? 

If I didn't feel deceived, then maybe I would feel a little at peace knowing that we have more financial support now, if we should ever need it.
LEAS.4b: Maybe he would feel a little bit nervous to tell me-given that this is a huge part of his background. I think he would feel relieved after telling me, and seeing my reaction.

LEAS.1a: I would be elated to find out that I did a good enough job to impress my employer, and it'd likely encourage me to keep that particular work ethic going for the future.

LEAS.3b: Probably relieved that I accepted their change of heart without throwing a fit about it. Who can blame them? It's a big risk, I imagine it would take some courage to stick your hard earned cash into something that might flop, friend beside you or not.
LEAS.4a: I'd understand it, no one wants to only be loved for money. I wouldn't be mad, I don't think - I'd be a bit perturbed about the secret keeping, but at least they were honest in the end, and keeping a secret about something like that isn't unreasonable. I guess though, in a way I'd be really relieved because it would mean that if something went wrong, we had something to fall back on and wouldn't end up immediately homeless.
LEAS.4b: They'd likely be happy and relieved that I wasn't angry. Some people would be really peeved that they were lied to, so they took a risk here.

LEAS.1a: I would feel very happy that my hard work was noticed. Having my work acknowledged by my superiors is important to me, so when I get compliments on my work ethic or quality of work, it motivates me to keep doing my best.
LEAS.1b: I imagine my boss would feel happy to have an employee who delivers excellent work. I also imagine that my happy reaction would help my boss to feel like they're doing a great job as a manager by motivating their employees with positive feedback.
LEAS.2a: I would feel disappointed that I failed to meet expectations. Initially, I would probably feel like I was not smart enough or skilled enough for my job, especially if I had tried my hardest to submit quality work. But after acknowledging and accepting those negative feelings, I believe I would want to follow up with my boss to see where I can improve and grow as a professional. I would also want to be mindful of what my boss might be going through. Certain circumstances might push them to be overly critical, such as personal or professional stress, mental health issues, lack of sleep, etc. If I believed my boss was being overly critical because of their own personal issues, I would not take the comment personally and be more concerned over their well-being.
LEAS.2b: Everyone is different in where they come from and context is key. If they said these things from a place of wanting to encourage their employee to do better, I imagine that they would feel satisfied for saying what was on their mind and addressing the issue with feedback. If they said these things because they were having a bad day and wanted to take it out on an employee, I imagine they would feel more powerful and in control of others by affecting someone else's emotions.
LEAS.3a: I would understand. I might be annoyed at first, but I would feel glad that my friend was able to express themselves to me so that we could avoid future conflicts. I would also want to follow up and understand why they might have changed their mind.
LEAS.3b: My friend would probably feel relieved to let that off their chest and for not being trapped in a situation where they were forced to do something that they didn't want to do. They might feel guilty for letting another person down or for not following through with what they said they would do.
LEAS.4a: If I'm in love, I would love them regardless of their financial state. I would feel more intrigued to get to know them and their family better before committing to marriage. I might also feel slightly intimidated. I'd also feel honored that they would entrust me with their secret.

I would hope that revealing a large secret like that would also allow them to feel more secure in the relationship. They would also probably feel very vulnerable and perhaps a bit scared and anxious about the way their partner responds.

LEAS.1a: I would feel as though my ego would be lifted by a lot. I would get very prideful and feel the need to tell anyone and everyone I can. It's not necessarily to brag but rather to feel warm and gooey inside reliving the moment over and over in multiple conversations throughout the day. I would feel more accomplished than most people because I struggle with self confidence so when I receive praise, I like to really bask in it. I believe that some people would feel the same as me if not more, however the majority, in my opinion, would feel good and move on to their next task.
LEAS.1b: If my boss is the one giving praise then something very good must have been done on my part. When I give praise to my friends, I feel proud when I see their happiness. I can only assume that the boss felt a high level of pride and happiness toward their employee.
LEAS.2a: I would immediately feel the need to prove myself. I cannot stand being looked down on or having people think of me in any negative way. I have a lot of problems with self confidence and insecurities. If I am told that my work is horrible, I feel as though I would go to a lower internal place than other people. If I do something wrong (in my eyes), I punish myself mentally and go to a really bad place within myself. I would wallow for some time and then push myself back up in order to get out of that place. I always get out of my funk no matter how long it takes, and once I do, I push back harder. I crave attention and love so I do whatever I can to reach it.
LEAS.2b: I think my boss would feel some sense of repulsion and disappointment. "Unacceptable" is a very harsh, extreme criticism so in order for "unacceptable" and "needs to be improved" to be said, I feel as though I must have done something completely wrong. I sometimes feel as though peoples emotions and feelings are always justified, meaning there is always a reason behind every human interaction, both physical and emotional. So if my boss was that heavily upset with me, I couldn't think of it as being a wrong or inaccurate feeling towards me but rather I MUST have done something wrong and I HAVE to fix it.
LEAS.3a: I don't think I would feel too upset. I am very hesitant when it comes to money and investing, so I probably would not have been 100% ready to go through with the business deal. Whenever friends back out of any kind of plans or deals, I never get too upset with them since I tend to make excuses for those around me. Internally, I'm contemplating wether they don't want to hang out with me, don't trust me with the deal, have something better as an option elsewhere, etc.. I would destroy my mind worrying about WHY. I wouldn't be upset about the business venture falling through but rather why did my friend pull out.
LEAS.3b: Since I am in constant paranoia about what my friends think regarding me at all times, it is hard for me to imagine what my friend would feel when backing out since I would personally believe a plethora of reasons why. If it was genuine then I do think my friend would express regret and sadness for letting me down but I feel as though (personally) I would misinterpret. Knowing my friends, however, I know deep down inside that if it was nerves that come with making money investments, they would tell me very open and honestly because if you really know me, you know that I am extremely skeptical of money investments.
LEAS.4a: I would never consider something like that a "lie". Many people would try to take advantage of that person so in order to find a true and genuine relationship, that person would need to protect themselves from untrue people. If we were struggling beyond believe and I was trying my hardest to keep up afloat, then I would feel a small sense of betrayal since I would be working myself to death only to find out that there was a small escape. I feel as though not telling your s/o about something that could make them take advantage of you at the beginning of a relationship is totally rational since their protecting themselves emotionally. If my income was adequate and this person was intelligent, I feel as though I would be happy regardless of their money/stature. I value the intellect and meaningful conversations in a shabby apartment rather than the bliss of ignorance in a million dollar mansion.
LEAS.4b: If my partner truly loved me and was only trying to protect himself from the greed and malice of other people, I think that they would feel a strong love for me in order to be able to free themselves from the guilt of not being true about who they are. It is a big burden to bear to hide something as significant as money and wealth. It must be on the tip of their tongue every second to come clean once they realise that their partner is truly in love for the person they are and not their materialistic counterpart. I think they would feel an immense sense of relief to be able to show who they really are. It isn't a lie to with hold information (in my eyes). I would want my partner to be able to fully love and trust in me and I would feel blessed for them to be able to share something like that with me. It would show me that that person is real towards me.

diagnosis.list_5: Major Depressive Disorder (MDD) w/o Psychotic Features
LEAS.1a: If I was working on a project for several months and my boss said my work was excellent I would firstly feel relieved especially after the few days waiting to hear back. Long projects are difficult for me especially when It come to staying focused on a long term goal and the fear of failure often time prevents me from getting work done so a project over months would be very difficult. After the initial feeling of relief that I had met expectations and I would get to keep my job (assuming I would be fired if my work was not excellent) I would secondly feel proud of myself for growing in my career and pushing myself to do the project and I would feel like a celebration was in store after leaving work for the day.
LEAS.1b: My boss would feel proud of themselves and their team including myself. My boss would probably pride his/her self for hiring an employee that did excellent work and probably attribute some of the projects success to themselves and their management skills. They would also feel relieved they no longer have to oversee the long project and be excited to come up with whatever work would come next. My boss would also feel exhausted after having to convey what they wanted for the project in such a specific way over a long period of time making sure I did an excelent job. And even after my part was done my boss still had to take days to review the project after submitting it and they're probably glad its over with.
LEAS.2a: I would feel crushed, a job is a big part of my life and I relate my job performance and work ethic as a core component of my personality because I pride myself on always working on something productive and producing great work. In addition I would feel almost betrayed by my boss for not seeing the effort I put in and rather than helping me to do a better job they just told me it was unacceptable. I would be stressed about the possibility of losing my job and being unable to pay bills. I would feel Isolated assuming my coworkers didn't like me because no one likes a co-worker that cant pull their weight. I want to say I would feel motivated to do better but I don't think this comment would motivate me it would make me sad and feel like I lacked value in the workplace.
LEAS.2b: My boss would feel frustrated because running a company with an employee that isn't pulling their weight makes it much harder to handle. They have a lot on their plate already and most likely already feel overwhelmed. They may also feel nervous to confront me about my poor performance out of fear I will not listen to them or take them seriously. They may also feel sad about having to tell me my work needs improvement because they like me as a person but cant let that get in the way of executing their job. Feelings of stress would probably dominate my boss though because they may need to do additional paperwork documenting my poor performance. This added time spent on the job acts as yet another stressor for my boss.
LEAS.3a: I would feel dissopointed that our idea would not be able to come to life but I wouldn't hold it against my friend, its a big undertaking and it had been several days but in the grand scheme of things that is not that long and maybe they should've taken longer to think about the idea.
LEAS.3b: my friend would feel guilty, regretful and stressed to tell me the news and that's likely why they hadn't called me first. The friend has to deal with their own dissopointment that the idea wont manifest but they also carry the weight of having to let a close friend down unknowing how I would react. The friend probably feels guilty for making the best move for themselves because it was at the expense of another person.
LEAS.4a: I feel blindsided and hurt on the deepest level. Someones financial upbringing has a lot to do with their development and their story as a person and to lie or omit the truth about something a fundemntal as family would be mind boggling. It doesn't matter that my income was adequate and they didn't contribute im upset about being lied to only to find out when discussing a forever commitment. I feel sad knowing the version of someone I fell in love with is not the person im discussing marriage with. I'm questioning this persons honesty in every aspect, what else don't I know? or what would they keep from me in the future? Was I blinded by their attractiveness and intelligence that I was blind to the lies and manupliation. For a moment I can put myself in his/her shoes and understand not wanting someone to love you for your money but this could've been disclosed after the first time saying "I love you" or even before. Waiting until now was selfish of that person and I feel like it has tainted my love for this person.
LEAS.4b: He/ she would likely feel overwhelming stress and guilt mixed with regret and despair. They likely know waiting until now was a mistake and this is a secrete that could potentially cause much animosity and ruin the relationship. This person probably feels torn because their honest attempt to guard their heart in the beginning of the relationship could be the very thing that puts them in a position to be hurt the worst. This person is likely ready to "fix" this with their money and buy back the other persons love and apologize. I have to believe this person thinks this conversation will go well or they would've brought it up sooner, unless there were mortified they would lie about something so fundamental.

LEAS.1a: I would feel proud and assured, however, my boss's approval is not indicative of how I feel about my success. It would make me feel good about my efforts, though.
LEAS.1b: It depends on why he/she is saying it. They could be saying it to encourage me, even though my work wasn't all that great, but they found what was good about it and complimented it. Typically, when someone is able to give a compliment, they are secure enough to do so, so they wouldn't feel threatened. I suspect my boss would be feeling some sort of pride, or possibly compassion. Me being able to interpret how they feel relies on my relationship with them, how well I know them, and observation of previous behaviors to be able to cross-examine with. It's possible that they just feel good and said that to make someone else feel good, and that makes them feel good. Sometimes people have complex reasons for doing things, other times, not so much. It's very hard to tell what a stranger is actually saying/feeling with 100% accuracy though, (Talking With Strangers, Malcom Gladwell)
LEAS.2a: I would feel discouraged, but would quickly remember the many reasons my boss might have said that. I would show happiness to improve and ask more questions to figure out what the problem is.
LEAS.2b: My boss would probably feel frustrated. For whatever reason, whether its the reason that sounds good, or the real reason, he/she is probably feeling frustrated.
LEAS.3a: Depends on how invested we are, and how much into it we were. Investing is pragmatic, so if he/she is someone I would do business with, the reason they have is probably a good one. I probably wouldn't feel much, as our friendship doesn't hinge on business. I would feel slightly disappointed, but that's about it. Also, never go into business with family/friends. Important guideline to keep in mind.
LEAS.3b: If a couple of days later, they are disinterested, they probably didn't have a lot of emotion invested into it in the first place, but they might have. It depends on their reasoning. I don't think I can answer how they feel without knowing more about the scenario. I would imagine apathetic, but all that is an assumption, speculation, which doesn't usually pan out too well when relied upon heavily.
LEAS.4a: I would feel more attracted to them. Wise choice, understandable.
LEAS.4b: Telling me, they would probably feel hesitant, as it has taken this long for them to feel comfortable opening up. Hopefully their tension would be eased after learning of my respect for that decision.
